2026-04-16 12:33:55 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor (control) module internal ground return / wiring', 'ambient sensor (control) module PCB ground trace near relay and output circuits'] hypothesis_explanation='The PSU output and the control module input pads both have a correct 11.99 V / 0 V supply referenced to the system ground. However, when referenced to the control module’s own internal ground node at the relay/rail, the so‑called “negative” side of the relay rail sits at about +0.36 V instead of 0 V. Correspondingly, only ~0.36 V is measured between the control module output + terminal and its − terminal, and the same low voltage appears at the load module input. This means that almost the entire 12 V from the PSU is being dropped somewhere between the control module input negative pad and the internal return node used by the relay and switched output, leaving only ~0.36 V across the load and output terminals. The relay itself is reported mechanically closed, and no extra drops are seen across relay path components; thus the fault is not in the relay contacts but in the control module’s ground path. The most consistent explanation is an open or very high‑resistance ground return inside the control module (broken PCB trace, bad solder joint, or connector fault on the internal negative line) so the module’s internal ground floats up close to +12 V through internal circuitry, collapsing the effective output voltage to ~0.36 V. Repairing/replacing the faulty ground return circuitry inside the ambient sensor (control) module should restore proper 0 V reference and allow the full 12 V to reach the load.'
